 1349":"efter 1349","1260":"1260","1392":"1392","1291":"1291","1338":"1338","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1323":"1323","about 1349":"omkring 1349","1322":"1322","about 1325":"omkring 1325","1453":"1453","about 1315":"omkring 1315","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Flamborough, Yorkshire, England":"Flamborough, Jórvík, England","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Jórvík, England","Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England":"Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England","Beesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Beesby, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1291–Aft 1349":"circa 1291–na 1349","1291–1349":"1291–1349","1295–Male":"1295–Overleden","1315–1392":"1315–1392","1315–Male":"1315–Overleden","1322–1338":"1322–1338","1323–Male":"1323–Overleden","1325–1392":"1325–1392","1260–1349":"1260–1349","about 1291":"circa 1291","1295":"1295","Aft 1349":"na 1349","1260":"1260","1392":"1392","1291":"1291","1338":"1338","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1323":"1323","about 1349":"circa 1349","1322":"1322","about 1325":"circa 1325","1453":"1453","about 1315":"circa 1315","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Flamborough, Yorkshire, England":"Flamborough, Yorkshire, England","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England","Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England":"Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England","Beesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Beesby, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1291–Aft 1349":"about 1291–after 1349","1291–1349":"1291–1349","1295–Male":"1295–Deceased","1315–1392":"1315–1392","1315–Male":"1315–Deceased","1322–1338":"1322–1338","1323–Male":"1323–Deceased","1325–1392":"1325–1392","1260–1349":"1260–1349","about 1291":"about 1291","1295":"1295","Aft 1349":"after 1349","1260":"1260","1392":"1392","1291":"1291","1338":"1338","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1323":"1323","about 1349":"about 1349","1322":"1322","about 1325":"about 1325","1453":"1453","about 1315":"about 1315","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Flamborough, Yorkshire, England":"Flamborough, Yorkshire, England","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England","Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England":"Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England","Beesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Beesby, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Skipwith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Surrey): variant of   Skipworth  .","History: The main Skipwith family held the manor of Skipwith in England in the early Middle Ages, and direct descendants can be traced to the present day. In the 13th century they moved from Yorkshire to Lincolnshire, where their principal seat was at southern Ormsby. In the early 17th century there was further migration, to Leicestershire, Warwickshire, and across the Atlantic to VA. Other bearers of the name seem to have been tenants of Lincolnshire manors held by the Skipworth family, and to have taken the surname of their overlords."],"variants":[{"name":"Skipworth","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): habitational name from Skipwith (East Yorkshire), from Old Northumbrian <i>scīp</i> (Old English <i>scēap</i> ‘sheep’), + Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farm’, later replaced by Old Norse <i>vithr</i> ‘wood’; initial <i>Sk-</i>, instead of <i>Sh-</i>, is also due to Scandinavian influence."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":24,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":37,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":46,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William Skipwith was born about 1291, in Lincolnshire, England as the son of John de Skipwith. He married Margaret Fitzsimon of Ormsby in 1315, in Flamborough, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died after 1349, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1291–Aft 1349":"umbes 1291–pärast 1349","1291–1349":"1291–1349","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1315–1392":"1315–1392","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1322–1338":"1322–1338","1323–Male":"1323–Surnud","1325–1392":"1325–1392","1260–1349":"1260–1349","about 1291":"umbes 1291","1295":"1295","Aft 1349":"pärast 1349","1260":"1260","1392":"1392","1291":"1291","1338":"1338","1349":"1349","1315":"1315",